cs of regular commercial air service delayed its inception until the 1930s. Technological, managerial and logistical problems also meant that Britain was slow into the air and slow in the air. Propaganda concealed underperformance and criticism. The study uses archival sources, biographies, industry magazines and newspapers to chronicle the disputed progress toward air empire. The rhetoric behind imperial air service offers a glimpse of late imperial hopes, fears, attitudes and style. Empire air service had emotional appeal and symbolic value, but disappointed in practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAeronautics, CommercialxPolitical aspectszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican arc.  aAlan Cobham.  aBritish imperialism.  aEastern crescent.  aEmpire civil aviation.  aImperial Airways.  aSefton Brancker.  aair empire.  aairway pioneering.  apropagation.  areconfiguration.  aroute organisation.  aroute reconnaissance.  atransformation.1 aPirie, Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611849340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526118493423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526118493/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles